('insilico-medicine', 'Insilico Medicine', 'End-to-end AI drug discovery platform from target identification to clinical candidate generation',
 E'Insilico Medicine is one of the most advanced AI-first drug discovery companies in the world, combining generative AI for molecular design, transformer models for target identification, and reinforcement learning for lead optimization into a single integrated platform called Pharma.AI. The company made history in 2023 by advancing an AI-designed drug candidate - ISM001-055 for idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis - into Phase II clinical trials, demonstrating that AI-generated molecules can clear the full preclinical hurdle and reach human testing faster and at a fraction of the traditional cost.\n\nThe Pharma.AI platform is organized into three modules. PandaOmics uses AI to analyze multi-omics datasets and clinical data to identify novel drug targets and rank them by novelty, druggability, and disease relevance. Chemistry42 is the generative chemistry module - given a validated target, it generates diverse molecular structures optimized for binding affinity, selectivity, solubility, and ADMET properties simultaneously. InClinico uses AI to predict clinical trial success probability for a given compound and indication, helping teams make better go/no-go decisions before committing to expensive Phase II and III studies.\n\nFor pharmaceutical companies and biotech investors evaluating AI drug discovery partnerships, Insilico represents the benchmark for what end-to-end AI pharma looks like in practice rather than in theory. The platform is available as a commercial research collaboration service rather than a self-serve SaaS product. Insilico targets rare diseases, oncology, and aging-related indications where the traditional 12-year drug development timeline creates the most acute need for AI acceleration.',
 'https://insilico.com', 'https://insilico.com',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.6, 520, false, true, false,
 ARRAY['biotech', 'drug-discovery', 'ai-research'],
 ARRAY['End-to-end AI platform covering target identification, molecular design, and clinical prediction', 'Phase II clinical proof-of-concept with AI-designed IPF drug candidate ISM001-055', 'Chemistry42 generates novel molecular structures optimized for multiple drug-like properties simultaneously', 'InClinico clinical success predictor reduces costly late-stage go/no-go decision errors'],
 ARRAY['Platform is accessed via research collaboration, not self-serve SaaS - requires partnership engagement', 'Best suited to pharma companies and large biotechs with existing drug discovery infrastructure', 'AI-generated candidates still require full traditional preclinical and clinical validation', 'Pricing and timelines require enterprise negotiation - not accessible to early-stage startups independently'],
 ARRAY['AI-accelerated drug target identification from multi-omics and clinical datasets', 'Generative molecular design for novel small-molecule drug candidates in rare and complex diseases', 'Clinical trial success prediction for portfolio prioritization and resource allocation decisions'],
 NOW()),

('benevolentai', 'BenevolentAI', 'AI knowledge graph platform for drug discovery and target identification in complex diseases',
 E'BenevolentAI builds AI-powered drug discovery capabilities around a proprietary biomedical knowledge graph that integrates scientific literature, clinical data, genomics, and experimental results into a structured, queryable representation of biological knowledge. The platform - called the Benevolent Platform - continuously ingests and synthesizes published scientific data to surface non-obvious connections between genes, proteins, diseases, and potential therapeutic mechanisms that human researchers would not identify by reading literature alone.\n\nThe knowledge graph approach has produced commercially validated results: BenevolentAI identified baricitinib (an existing JAK inhibitor) as a potential COVID-19 treatment in early 2020, several months before clinical evidence emerged. The same approach is applied to identifying novel targets in oncology, neurodegeneration, immunology, and cardiology - diseases where the complexity of the biological pathways involved makes manual hypothesis generation slow and incomplete. Target hypothesis generation is followed by AI-guided experimental design recommendations that prioritize which assays and animal models are most likely to validate or invalidate the hypothesis efficiently.\n\nBenevolentAI operates as both a commercial platform provider and an internal drug discovery company - it runs its own clinical pipeline alongside licensing the platform to pharmaceutical partners. The commercial model for external partners involves technology licensing and research collaboration agreements. For drug discovery teams exploring AI-augmented target biology and indication expansion on existing molecules, the Benevolent Platform represents a peer-reviewed, commercially active approach rather than a theoretical AI research tool.',
 'https://benevolent.ai', 'https://benevolent.ai',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.4, 310, false, true, false,
 ARRAY['biotech', 'drug-discovery', 'ai-research'],
 ARRAY['Biomedical knowledge graph integrates literature, genomics, and clinical data into queryable biology', 'Validated commercial success: identified baricitinib for COVID-19 treatment from data signals alone', 'Target hypothesis generation surfaces non-obvious biological connections across disease areas', 'Dual model - internal pipeline plus external licensing - validates the platform in real drug programs'],
 ARRAY['Access via partnership and licensing agreements - not a self-serve research tool', 'Knowledge graph quality depends on continuous literature ingestion - niche disease areas have less data density', 'Platform is most valuable for target identification phase - less differentiated at later medicinal chemistry stages', 'Commercial terms require enterprise negotiation; budget expectations should be set at pharma scale'],
 ARRAY['Novel drug target identification in complex diseases using AI-connected biological knowledge', 'Indication expansion analysis for existing approved molecules seeking new therapeutic applications', 'Hypothesis prioritization for research teams choosing between competing target hypotheses in limited budgets'],
