('schrodinger', 'Schrodinger', 'Physics-based computational platform for molecular simulation and drug design',
 E'Schrodinger is the leading provider of physics-based molecular simulation software for drug discovery and materials science. Unlike machine learning approaches that predict molecular properties from pattern recognition alone, Schrodinger''s platform uses quantum mechanical calculations and molecular dynamics simulations to model how drug molecules interact with protein targets at the atomic level. This physics-first approach produces more reliable predictions for novel chemical series where training data is sparse - a critical advantage in drug discovery where the most valuable candidates are often structurally unprecedented.\n\nThe platform suite covers the full structure-based drug design workflow: protein structure preparation and binding site analysis (Glide, Prime), free energy perturbation calculations for precise binding affinity prediction (FEP+), ADMET property prediction (QikProp, ADME), and generative molecular design (LiveDesign, Maestro). In 2026, Schrodinger has integrated deep learning components alongside its physics models - using AI to pre-filter large virtual compound libraries before applying expensive quantum calculations, dramatically improving throughput without sacrificing accuracy.\n\nSchrodinger serves pharmaceutical companies, biotechs, and academic research institutions through software licensing and through collaborative drug discovery programs. The company has an active internal drug discovery pipeline and has co-discovered compounds now in clinical trials with partners including Bristol Myers Squibb, Takeda, and Pfizer. For medicinal chemists working on structure-based drug design programs, Schrodinger represents the gold standard for computational accuracy when the structural biology is known and the target is well-characterized.',
 'https://schrodinger.com', 'https://schrodinger.com',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.5, 680, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['biotech', 'drug-discovery', 'ai-research'],
 ARRAY['Physics-based molecular simulation provides mechanistic accuracy that pure ML approaches cannot match', 'FEP+ free energy calculations deliver the most reliable binding affinity predictions in the industry', 'Integrated AI acceleration reduces computational cost by pre-filtering candidates before expensive quantum calculations', 'Co-discovery partnerships with Pfizer, BMS, and Takeda validate commercial drug program applications'],
 ARRAY['Computational resources required for FEP+ calculations are significant - cloud or HPC infrastructure needed', 'Highest value when high-quality protein structures are available - less differentiated for challenging targets', 'Software licensing costs are substantial; academic and SMB pricing differs from pharma enterprise rates', 'Physics-based approaches are slower per candidate than pure ML generative methods for initial screening'],
 ARRAY['Structure-based lead optimization where precise binding affinity prediction determines candidate selection', 'Virtual screening of compound libraries against validated drug targets to identify starting scaffolds', 'ADMET property prediction and metabolic stability assessment for medicinal chemistry design decisions'],
 NOW()),

('atomwise', 'Atomwise', 'Deep learning platform for small-molecule drug discovery and virtual screening at scale',
 E'Atomwise pioneered the application of convolutional neural networks to molecular docking and virtual screening, building a deep learning platform - AtomNet - that predicts protein-ligand binding affinity faster and more accurately than traditional docking algorithms. The core application is ultra-large-scale virtual screening: AtomNet can screen billions of commercially available or synthesizable compounds against a protein target in days rather than the months traditional computational methods require, identifying the most promising hits for experimental validation.\n\nThe AIMS (Atomwise Integrated Modeling System) platform extends beyond virtual screening to include protein structure prediction, binding site identification, selectivity profiling across the proteome, and lead optimization guidance. Atomwise has screened over 3 million targets for pharmaceutical, biotech, and academic partners through its research collaboration model, generating more than 1,600 drug discovery programs across oncology, infectious disease, and neurological disorders.\n\nThe ADSC (Artificial Intelligence Molecular Screen) collaboration program is a notable differentiator: academic researchers and small biotechs can submit protein targets for AI screening under a research collaboration agreement, accessing AtomNet screening capabilities that would otherwise require the computational infrastructure of a major pharmaceutical company. For drug discovery teams at academic medical centers and early-stage biotechs that cannot afford full Schrodinger or Insilico platform subscriptions, Atomwise provides a path to AI-powered virtual screening at accessible entry points. The company has also deployed AtomNet for antiviral discovery programs and published results in peer-reviewed journals, providing external validation of the platform''s screening accuracy.',
 'https://atomwise.com', 'https://atomwise.com',
 'paid', false, NULL, 4.3, 290, false, false, false,
 ARRAY['biotech', 'drug-discovery', 'ai-research'],
 ARRAY['AtomNet screens billions of compounds against protein targets in days rather than months', 'ADSC collaboration program provides AI screening access to academic and early-stage biotech teams', 'Over 3 million targets screened across 1,600+ drug discovery programs provides broad validation', 'Proteome-wide selectivity profiling identifies off-target binding risks before experimental synthesis'],
 ARRAY['Platform access requires research collaboration agreement - not a self-serve virtual screening tool', 'Deep learning predictions still require wet-lab validation - experimental false positive rates remain significant', 'Best suited to early-stage hit identification - later-stage lead optimization requires additional computational methods', 'Academic collaboration terms and timelines depend on program prioritization within Atomwise'],
